uitability** | Eats unhealthily (health concern) | Pretentious (interpersonal concern) | Not very willing to further his education (development concern) | Moody, loner (interpersonal concern) |\n**Key observations**\n1. **Reliability and calmness** are non\u2011negotiable for long\u2011distance international flights. Candidate\u202fB is the only one with explicit statements for both (100\u202f% reliable and calm in a crisis). Candidate\u202fC is calm but lacks any reliability claim.\n2. **Technical competence** is strong across the board, but B\u2019s weather\u2011assessment skill and computer proficiency are directly relevant to modern long\u2011haul operations.\n3. **Teamwork/communication** is a weakness for every candidate. B\u2019s negative statements (nasty remarks, wrong tone) are serious, yet they are the only documented teamwork issues for B. C has both negative (communication difficulty, egocentric) and positive (creates a positive crew atmosphere, strong concern for others) aspects. A and D have only negative interpersonal traits and no mitigating positives.\n4. **Overall risk profile** \u2013 The combination of proven reliability, calmness under pressure, and essential technical skills makes Candidate\u202fB the safest choice despite his documented interpersonal shortcomings. These shortcomings, while important, do not outweigh the lack of reliability or calmness in the other candidates.\n**Conclusion:** Based on the explicit evidence, I recommend selecting **Candidate\u202fB** for the long\u2011distance pilot position.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate B\"}", "thoughts": "We need to respond as agent_2. We have to follow the system instruction: we can ask other agents for missing info, then produce public contribution and vote. We have already seen that other agents have provided info about calmness for A and D (none). We have all explicit facts for each candidate. However, we might still be missing some positive teamwork in